==English==
===Etymology===
From ancient Greek [[Ωκεανός]] (''okeanos'') "ocean", from [[ωκυς]] (''okys'') "fast, quick, swift" + [[ναω]] (''nao'') " to flow, to flux". In Greek mythology [[Ωκεανός]] was the first-born of the Titans, the personification of the god [[Ωκεανός]] [[Ποταμός]] "River Ocean", that encircled the earth.

===Proper noun===
'''Oceanus'''
{{wikipedia}}
#{{greekmyth}}: Personification of vast waters, or the world ocean, he was a [[Titan]] son of [[Uranus]] and [[Gaia]], and with his sister [[Tethys]] fathered all rivers and the [[Oceanids]].


